# No Backward Compatibility Until the Project Is Open

Until this project is open to external developers, **do not protect or preserve old implementations for backward-compatibility reasons**. If a better implementation exists, replace the old one directly.

**Replace, don't wrap:**
- Change function signatures when a better one exists.
- Delete code that is superseded. Do not keep it "for backward compatibility."
- Do not add parallel APIs (e.g. a "legacy" and a "new" version of the same thing) unless the two serve genuinely distinct purposes.

**Two narrow exceptions where the original must be preserved:**
1. **Historical algorithm fidelity**: When replicating a specific published algorithm (e.g. 1980s yolk/heart algorithms from Miller, Feld, Grofman et al.), the original logic must be preserved and its source cited. Improvements go in separate, clearly-named functions.
2. **Externally-sourced code brought in verbatim**: treat as read-only unless you have explicit permission to modify.

**When the project opens to other developers**, this rule is superseded by standard semantic versioning and deprecation policy (see `milestone_gates.md` § First binding / 1.0 and ROADMAP.md § Documentation and citation standards).
